{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17595344","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17595344"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T11:03:32+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T11:03:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15351"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15351","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15351"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.19,0.27,0.5,0.04,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8042"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67896"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8042","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8042"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15351"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53361"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"7567"},{"type":"tags","id":"8127"},{"type":"tags","id":"8762"},{"type":"tags","id":"9270"},{"type":"tags","id":"9616"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19532"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19535"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22739"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67896","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/67896"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA two-week-old infant presents with jaundice. Blood tests show elevated unconjugated bilirubin with normal conjugated bilirubin.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Alpha-1 antitrypsin deficiency","Biliary atresia","Breast milk jaundice","Choledochal cyst","Sepsis"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most likely explanation for this infant\u0027s problem is breast milk jaundice.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBreast milk jaundice\u003C/strong\u003E is a common cause of unconjugated hyperbilirubinaemia in breastfed infants, typically presenting after day 4-7 of life and persisting for several weeks. It is thought to be caused by substances in breast milk that inhibit bilirubin conjugation or increase enterohepatic circulation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBiliary atresia\u003C/strong\u003E, \u003Cstrong\u003Echoledochal cyst\u003C/strong\u003E, \u003Cstrong\u003Esepsis\u003C/strong\u003E, and \u003Cstrong\u003Ealpha-1 antitrypsin deficiency\u003C/strong\u003E all typically present with conjugated hyperbilirubinaemia due to impaired bile flow or hepatocellular dysfunction. These conditions represent serious pathology requiring urgent investigation and management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe pattern of hyperbilirubinaemia (conjugated vs unconjugated) is crucial in differentiating between benign and serious causes of jaundice in infants.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Unconjugated hyperbilirubinaemia after 10 days of age is most commonly due to breast milk jaundice","Conjugated hyperbilirubinaemia suggests hepatobiliary pathology requiring urgent investigation","Biliary atresia, choledochal cysts, and sepsis typically cause conjugated hyperbilirubinaemia"],"references":["Chee YY, Chung PH, Wong RM, Wong KK. Jaundice in infants and children: causes, diagnosis, and management. Hong Kong Med J. 2018 Jun;24(3):285-292. doi: 10.12809/hkmj187245. Epub 2018 May 21. PMID: 29807950","Ansong-Assoku B, Shah SD, Adnan M, et al. Neonatal Jaundice. [Updated 2024 Feb 12]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK532930/","Mitra S, Rennie J. Neonatal jaundice: aetiology, diagnosis and treatment. Br J Hosp Med (Lond). 2017 Dec 2;78(12):699-704. doi: 10.12968/hmed.2017.78.12.699. PMID: 29240507"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53361"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15351"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53361","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/53361"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-07T18:35:53+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-07T18:36:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8042"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67896"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tag